+
+## 2024-06-13 - [Firestore Race Condition in Unauthenticated Setup Endpoint]
+**Vulnerability:** The `/setup` endpoint allowed creating a `superadmin` user and writing the setup lock document (`_setup/config`) sequentially. The `firestore.rules` permitted this based solely on `isSetupOpen()` (which checks `!exists(...)` of the lock doc). An attacker could race the sequential requests or forge a single `setDoc` payload to create a superadmin without ever creating the lock document, leaving the system permanently open for further exploitation.
+**Learning:** Unauthenticated setup endpoints that grant maximum privileges must enforce strict atomicity on the server side. Relying on sequential client-side requests is insecure because the first request (user creation) succeeds independently of the second (locking the system).
+**Prevention:** Always enforce atomic batching in `firestore.rules` using `existsAfter` or `getAfter`. For setup scenarios, mandate that the creation of the high-privilege account MUST occur in the exact same transaction as the creation of the lock document (e.g., `allow create: if ... && existsAfter(/databases/$(database)/documents/_setup/config)`), and update the client to use `writeBatch`.
